column12: Security valve mechanism for a hydraulic system
column13: A lock mechanism for vehicles, such as cars, forklifts and earth moving equipment, having hydraulic systems for brakes, transmissions or clutches is disclosed. The mechanism includes a double non-return cam and hydraulic actuated valves which when closed retain fluid under pressure in the brake, transmission or clutch system, to prevent movement of the vehicle, such as by holding brakes on or clutches in the disengaged position.

column12: Improvements in or relating to desalination apparatus and method.
column13: Improvements in or relating to apparatus for the desalination of seawater. The invention relates to desalination apparatus which utilises solar energy and is thereby capable of continuously providing sufficient pure water for drinking, irrigation, etc. economically. A lagoon for seawater is heated by solar energy and the seawater is transferred to a vacuum boiler (30), steam being delivered through a turbine (54) to a condenser (22). The turbine (54) generates the power necessary for the running of the apparatus. Pure water is collected from the condenser (22) and the seawater remaining in the boiler (30) is returned to the lagoon through flexible tubes (14) arranged on a terraced support sloping down to the lagoon, the tubes (14) defining a collector for solar energy. The salinity balance in the seawater returned from the boiler (30) is maintained continuously by a flow circuit (44, 48) so arranged as to require no additional power consumption.
column15: SANDERS-FOX DOUGLAS

column12: Fetal speaker system and support belt for maternal wear
column13: A fetal speaker system and support belt of the present invention includes a belt like housing, a pair of low volume speakers mounted spaced apart, and a casing with a resilient padding material therein. The belt fastens around the abdomen and adjusts accordingly to the growing belly. A radio or other audio transmitting device is maintained in position by a sturdy sleeve on the side of the belt. The electrical conductor connecting the plug to the speakers is mounted within the casing such that the wires do not interfere with the belt wearer. The belt offers sturdy yet stain resistant material for the exterior and a comfortable soft cloth on the interior side to be worn on bare skin if desired. The material is available in a wide variety of fashionable colors and can be designed according to the individual's specifications.

column12: IMPROVEMENTS IN OR RELATING TO APPARATUS FOR BREAKING UP MATERIALS, PARTICULARLY STONE AND STONE-LIKE MATERIAL
column13: 1283961 Impact pulverisers BARDON HILL QUARRIES (LONDON) Ltd 14 July 1970 [19 April 1969] 20094/69 Heading B2A An impact pulverizer, particularly for comminuting minerals or nut shells, comprises a rotor 14, Fig. 1, and a stator casing 10. Fig. 2, including fragmentation chambers F. Each chamber F includes a sweeper wall 26 mounted in the rotor, and is bounded by inclined side walls 16 curved impact members 15, top wall segments 18, releasable covers 18 and a releasable bottom 12. The rotor compirses upper and lower discs 22, 23 bolted at 24 Fig. 3 and circumferentially-spaced impeller blades 25. The sweeper walls 26 are secured between the discs 22, 23 by bolts 27, Fig. 1, and may be resiliently mounted, e.g. on rubber. The casing has a central opening closed by a cover 28. The parts 16, 18, 26 may have ribbed or toothed surfaces. In operation, material enters the rotor from a box 29 via openings 30, is hurled by the blades 25 against the walls 15 and falls out via openings 31. The size of the product is determined by the speed of rotation of the rotor. Fan blades 32 draw in air via slots 33 and thus balance the internal pressures and prevent passage of excess dust across the parts. Entry of tramp metal causing an undesired out-of-balance effect may be used to operate an inertia switch stopping the apparatus and/or giving an alarm signal. The frame of the machine may be protected by hardened-steel toothed or ribbed elements. The working faces of the apparatus which are subject to extreme wear may be protected by tungsten carbide inserts dovetailed to the main components.

column12: CORROSION-RESISTANT ENCASEMENT FOR STRUCTURAL MEMBERS
column13: A protective system for concrete, wood and steel piling or other structures subject to corrosion or wear from the action of water. The system includes an encasement sleeve surrounding the piling or other structure and made of fiberglass, epoxy resin, or other inert, corrosion resistant material, and a filler of concrete, epoxy resin or the like between the encasement sleeve and the piling. The encasement sleeve is made of separate sections connected together by tongue and groove joints. The encasement and filler are left permanently of the structure to protect the same from water of other elements, and also to reconstruct worn portions to achieve the original structural integrity of the structure.

Methods of producing the printed circuit board are also provided. The subject printed circuit board and methods find use in a variety of different applications, including electronics applications.

column12: PLASTIC FORM FOR MOULDING CONCRETE
column13: A system of elongate plastic forms which may be stacked and interconnected for a single pour of concrete to permeate through the system. The forms are connectable in end-to-end relation between tongue and groove connections and, in stacked relation, through further tongues and grooves. Prior to connecting the forms, holes may be cut in them to mate one with the other for flow of concrete when the forms are stacked. The forms have inwardly sloping front and rear faces to be narrower at the top than at the bottom and may be stacked to form a retaining wall having a flat front face sloping rearwardly with the same slope as that of the form front faces. Rear edges of the forms project into material to be retained behind the wall. 2893b/1

column12: Plastics corrosion-resistant encasement for structural members - is longitudinally split to permit application laterally to the member to be covered
column13: An encasement for a structural member comprises a jacket having at least one longitudinal split to permit lateral application to the member to be covered. The edges of the split fit together in tongue and groove fashion and are secured by a bonding material. A filler is cast between the jacket and the structural member. Jackets may be of glass fibre, PVC, epoxy, polyester or other plastics, and the filler may be a plastics such as an epoxy resin. The encasement is useful for protecting piles, pipes etc. both on land and submerged.

column12: Cable clamp for flat cables
column13: A cable clamp for a flat cable has a moulded base (fig. 1, not shown) and a moulded cover as shown, each of which is of the form of a shallow tray. The walls of the tray have projections (7, 8) and recesses so located that the base and the cover can be fitted together in snap-action manner. Three of the walls when fitted together have a shallow aperture via which a flat cable can pass so that the clamp can be fitted over a T-ed joint between two flat cables. One edge of each wall is curved with a large recess so that the cables are each gripped as they pass through an aperture but are not pinched. A crossed-cable clamp with four apertures is also disclosed. <IMAGE>

column12: Device for Administering a Gas to a Patient
column13: 1,169,203. Respiratory appliances. CAPE ENG. CO. Ltd. 27 June, 1967 [30 June, 1966], No. 29332/66. Heading. A5T. A device for administering air, oxygen, or anaesthetic gas to a patient comprises a bellows 1 fitted within a chamber 2, the bellows having a non-return inlet 4, 12 for the respiratory gas and a non-return outlet 5, 13 for passing the gas to the patient, the chamber being adapted to communicate with means 20 capable of alternately introducing a fluid under pressure into the chamber and extracting the fluid from the chamber, the chamber also having a non-return inlet 6, 19 through which gas exhaled by the patient may be drawn into the chamber, the non-return inlet being external of the chamber. As shown, the device also includes a bag 15 which may be used for manually introducing gas into the bellows, safety valves 7, 17, a pressure gauge 18 in either the outlet 5 or the inlet 6, and an outlet 22 having an adjustable pressure release valve opening to atmosphere. The bellows 1 is biased by a weight 3 or by a spring so that it inflates of its own accord and an adjustable calibrated stop 9, 10 limits the volume of gas supplied to the patient. The chamber 2 is of transparent material or is provided with a window so that the bellows 1 may be observed, and the gas is supplied to the patient, e.g. an infant, via the outlet 5 and either a face mask or a tent. It is stated that several bellows 1 may be provided within the chamber 2 so that the device may treat several patients simultaneously. The pump 20 providing fluid, e.g. air, at a cyclically varying pressure may run at any controlled rate and may comprise a mechanically driven ventilator, a hand operated collapsible bag, or the machine described in Specification 1,008,520.

column12: Improvements relating to conveyor systems
column13: 745,265. Roller conveyers; platform apparatus. VICKERS - ARMSTRONGS (ENGINEERS), Ltd. Sept. 15, 1954 [Sept. 21, 1953], No. 25962/53. Classes 78 (1) and 78 (3). A vertically-movable platform used for transporting stacks of crates from floor to floor in a building is moved stepby-step near the upper floor in order that the crates in each layer of the stack on the platform can be manually moved horizontally on to a conveyer or from a conveyer to form a stack on the platform. At the lower floor the crates, which are stacked on pallets, are brought by fork-truck to the platform. As the truck approaches the platform it is constrained by guide rails 12 to pass over a contact device 13, depression of which causes the door 5 to open. The truck is moved on to deposit the pallet on the platform. On withdrawal of the truck the contact device 13 is released, the lift door closes and a red signal light 16 goes out. The attendant then starts the hoisting mechanism and the lift rises until the top layer of crates is slightly above the conveyer 7. This layer is removed by an attendant who, when the removal is complete, actuates a pedal switch 14 to energize a relay causing the lift to rise one step, i.e. through the height of a crate. These operations are repeated until the lift is empty. When an attendant at the other side of the structure 6 actuates a pedal switch, the lift is lowered one step. It is then loaded with a layer of crates and the operation completed until the stack is complete. The lift is then lowered to floor 1 on reaching which it causes a green signal light 16 to come on to indicate that the lift requires unloading. The arrival of the truck causes the opening of the door and its withdrawal effects the closing of the door and the changing of the light from green to red. The roller conveyers 7, 8, Fig. 4, are made with hinged sections 25 which can be lifted to facilitate access to the crates.

column12: Improvements relating to automatic machines for filling vessels such as bottles withliquid
column13: 722,358. Bottling. WORSSAM & SON, Ltd., G. J. May 19, 1953 [June 16, 1952], No. 15127/52.' Class 125 (2). [Also in Group XXIX] In, e.g., a rotary counter-pressure bottling machine, an automatic valve for admitting liquid to the tank 5, Fig. 1, comprises a pressure sensitive device such as a diaphragm 26 for operating a liquid admission valve 1, which responds to a pressure derived from a source of substantially constant pressure external to the tank and which is controlled by a valve device 44, Fig. 4, sensitive to liquid level in the tank. Liquid enters at 14 to the inlet of the valve 1 and passes a snift valve whereby gas in the liquid enters a chamber 13 and depresses an annular float 16 carrying a valve 15 so that the gas escapes via the valve a hollow central float guide 17 and a cock 20. The valve 15 is closed by the float as liquid re-enters the chamber 13. A source of pressure air is supplied at 29 past a pressure reducing valve 30 and a valve 31 to a valve chamber 32 which leads via a line 33 to a diaphragm chamber 27. The valve chamber contains a needle air-throttle valve 34 and an adjustable spring-loaded, leak-off valve 44 operated through a push rod 38 by twin floats 35 responsive to the liquid level in the tank, so that as the level falls due to the bottles being filled via pipes 11 and filling head 12, the leak-off valve closes and air pressure moves the spring loaded diaphragm to open the valve 1 and admit liquid to the tank via the inlet pipe 7 and annular conical opening 8. Specification 503,926 is referred to.

column12: A Machine for the Administration of Anaesthetic Gases or for the Ventilation of a Patient
column13: 1,190,441. Respiratory apparatus. CAPE ENG. CO Ltd. 12 Feb., 1968 [10 Feb., 1967], No. 6464/67. Heading A5T. A machine for the administration of anaesthetic gases or for the ventilation of a patient includes pumping means 7 for effecting expiration of gas from the patient, ducting 6, 9 for conveying expired gas from the patient to the said means, a branch: pipe 16 leading from the ducting and a selector valve 19 operable to permit gas expired by the patient to flow either through the branch pipe or through the portion of the ducting downstream of the junction therewith of the branch pipe, there being means for connecting the branch pipe to a spirometer, or equivalent apparatus, for measuring the volume of expired gas or rate of expiration, cr to a sampling device, whereby sample of gas expired by a patient can be tested or analysed. As shown, the branch pipe 16 is connected in the dluct 6, 9 between valves 17 and 18 cf an otherwise known open-circuit anaesthetic machine or ventilator which comprises an air or anaesthetic gas inlet duct 1, a positive phase bellows 3, and a control valve 4 providing the air or gas through a pipe 9 to the patients face mask. An outlet duct 5 to atmosphere, a negative phase bellows 7 with a valve controlled by-pass 15, and a control valve 8 serve to remove the exhalation gas from the patient. The machine includes an oxygen inlet 10 and the bellows and control valves are operated by a shaft 12 from an electric motor 13 and gear 14. A spirometer 20, or other apparatus, is connected to the end of the branch pipe 16 and, by manually operating the selector valve 19, the volume of gas expired by the patient, or the rate of expiration may be measured or a gas sample may be obtained for analysis. The inlet duct 1 and the outlet duct 5 may be connected together so that the machine operates on closed circuit.

column12: Epicyclic gear system with flexpins
column13: A flexpin assembly (B) for an epicyclic gear system (A) includes a flexpin ( 20 ) that at one end is cantilevered from a carrier end wall ( 12 ) and a sleeve ( 22 ) that surrounds the flexpin and is cantilevered from the flexpin at the other end of the flexpin. In addition, the assembly has an antifriction bearing ( 24 ) for supporting a planet pinion ( 6 ) around the sleeve. The flexpin has a base ( 30 ) that is configured to be anchored to a carrier wall, a head ( 32 ) to which the sleeve is attached, and a shank ( 34 ) located between the base and head. The sleeve has a mounting segment ( 78 ) that is connected to the head of the flexpin without a weld. Both may have tapered surfaces secured in contact by a plate ( 66 ) clamped against the mounting portion with screws ( 68 ) that thread into the head, thus enabling the sleeve to be detached from the pin. The head may have a cylindrical surface ( 72 ) over which the mounting segment of the sleeve fits with an interference fit exists. The bearing may have rolling elements ( 106, 108 ) that surround raceways ( 86, 88 ) on the sleeve and a rib ring ( 94 ) that confines the rolling elements axially, but can be detached. The flexpin assembly is easily disassembled to facilitate servicing of the gear system.

column12: REEL FOR A HARVESTING MACHINE
column13: "REEL FOR A HARVESTING MACHINE" A reel for a harvesting machine comprises a plurality of bats arranged for rotation around an axis defined by a shaft. The bats are pivotal about a bat axis parallel to the shaft and are driven in pivoting movement by an eccentric ring member interconnected to each of the bats by a rigid link controlled by the eccentric ring member. The ring member is free to rotate relative to the shaft but is driven by each in turn of the links when the respective bat reaches an extreme position as defined by a sliding link coupled between the rigid link and the ring member. The bats comprise folded sheet metal in tubular form defining a plurality of pockets each for receiving a plastics finger for projecting from a leading edge of the bat. Each bat is formed from separate bat portions coupled together by tubes extending into an end of the bat and bolted to the tubes so as to depress material from the bat into a punched hole formed in a groove in the tube.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR WEATHER-BASED ACTIVITIES PLANNING AND ADVERTISING
column13: L'invention concerne un système et un procédé permettant de planifier en fonction du temps des activités et/ou des évènements à venir. Le système comprend des prévisions météorologiques, des antécédents climatiques, des activités, des annonces publicitaires et des bases de données de sources d'informations externes. Le système comprend également un serveur de planification central, accessible via plusieurs stations de travail internes et externes. Les stations de travail fournissent une interface utilisateur graphique permettant aux utilisateurs d'introduire une série d'entrées et de recevoir des données (c'est-à-dire, des sorties) sur des informations climatiques. Le procédé consiste à collecter les séries d'entrées - emplacement(s) géographique(s), tranche(s) horaire(s) et caractéristique(s) climatique(s) préférée(s) - affectant un évènement à venir.

column12: ADJUSTABLE FLOOR TO WALL CONNECTORS FOR USE WITH BOTTOM CHORD AND WEB BEARING JOISTS
column13: The present invention is a light steel framed metal joist including an adjustable connector fastened to the joist web that allows one to adjust the length and angle of the joist when attaching to floor and wall systems. The adjustment allows one to install end connectors onto the joists prior to installation while retaining flexibility of orientation during construction. The joist functions in both web bearing and bottom chord bearing configurations. A flat plate distributing member allows one to design a floor system without having to coordinate the positioning of the joist with wall studs. Angle or U shaped members can be fastened to the lower portion of the flat plate distribution member to support joists during construction. The invention further provides a seamless fire stopping system with consideration for acoustic dampening.

column12: VLS Fiber growth process
column13: A method for preparing substrates for VLS fiber producing reactions and a method for preparing SiC fibers by the VLS process. The first method includes the steps of forming an alcohol sol containing a fiber growth promoter material precursor, applying the sol to at least one surface of the substrate and drying the sol. More particularly, the steps can include forming a sol of colloidal hydrous metal oxide particles in a liquid, the metal oxide being a fiber growth promoter material precursor and the liquid being capable of dissolving a salt of the metal and of wetting the substrate surface as a sol, applying the sol to at least one surface of the substrate and drying the sol. The method for the production of SiC fibers includes the steps of applying to at least one surface of a non-metallic, high temperature resistant substrate a sol coating containing a SiC fiber growth promoter material precursor, drying the sol coating and contacting the substrate with silicon and carbon containing gases at a temperature of about 1300.degree. C. to about 1500.degree. C.

column12: SWEEP GENERATOR ERROR CHARACTERIZATION
column13: A delay time between the start of a trace on an oscilloscope screen and a point along the trace is computed based on measured "sweep gain" and "sweep start" parameters characterizing a triggered sweep signal controlling the horizontal position of an electron beam creating the trace, the sweep signal increasing when triggered from a starting level at a constant slew rate to move the beam at a constant speed across the screen. The sweep start parameter is the value of input data applied to a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) which would cause the DAC to produce an output voltage equal to the sweep signal starting level, and the sweep gain indicates the rate of increase in DAC input data required to produce a DAC output signal with a rate of increase similar to the slew rate of the sweep signal. The horizontal position of the point along the trace is the beam position on the screen at the moment the sweep signal magnitude reaches the magnitude of the DAC output signal. The delay time is computed as the difference between the DAC input data resulting in this DAC output signal magnitude and the sweep start parameter, the difference being divided by the sweep gain parameter.

column12: Ozone generation and water treatment
column13: Air is compressed in a compressor 1, cooled to ambient temperature in a heat exchanger 7, and (after separation of condensed water in a trap 9) is fed alternately through two desiccators 13, 14 to an expansion valve 18 which feeds dry air at approximately ambient pressure to an ozone generator 27. Excess compressed air is returned through a valve 21 to the inoperative one of the desiccators to expel moisture which has been collected. The ozone generator 27 has outer and inner tubular electrodes with a tubular insulator between them. A passageway for air to be ozonised is defined between at least one of tie electrodes and the insulator, and the electrode surface delimiting the passageway is provided with grooving. The ozone is used to treat water, which may then be electrolysed to generate hypochlorite ions from chloride ions present in the water (Fig. 11). <IMAGE>

column12: ADAPTOR FOR ATTACHMENT OF AN AGRICULTURAL IMPLEMENT TO A THREE POINT HITCH OF A TRACTOR
column13: ADAPTOR FOR ATTACHMENT OF AN AGRICULTURAL IMPLEMENT TO A THREE POINT HITCH OF A TRACTOR An adaptor for attachment of a swather header to a conventional tractor using the three point hitch available on the tractor comprises an elongate beam having brackets at one end for attachment to the three point hitch and a ground wheel at an opposed end for rolling upon the ground so that the beam is supported at the hitch at one end and the ground wheel at the other end. An arm extending from the beam to the ground wheel is directed downwardly and toward the tractor so that the wheel is approximately aligned with the rolling axis of the adjacent wheels of the tractor. This prevent scrubbing during steering. In addition the three point hitch is arranged relative to the angle of the arm so that lifting movement of the three point hitch rotates the beam about a longitudinal axis of the beam thus causing the arm to move downwardly by an amount equal to the upward movement of the beam to maintain the ground wheel properly on the ground and the beam level. The swather header is mounted upon the beam by a floating attachment system.

column12: MEDIOS DE FILTRACION Y METODO DE FABRICACION.
column13: LA INVENCION ACTUAL SE REFIERE A UN MATERIAL DE FILTRACION, Y MAS PARTICULARMENTE, A UNO QUE SEA IDONEO PARA FILTRACION DE AIRE EN LA CALEFACCION, VENTILACION, Y EN SISTEMAS DE AIRE ACONDICIONADO. EL PRIMER OBJETIVO DEL FILTRO DE AIRE DE ALTA EJECUCION ES EL DE PROPORCIONAR UNA RETIRADA MAXIMA DE PARTICULAS MIENTRAS MANTIENEN UNA CAIDA ACEPTABLE DE LA PRESION. LOS FILTROS FIBROSOS CONVENCIONALES OBTIENEN UNA EFICACIA DE RETIRADA DE PARTICULAS MEJORADA UTILIZANDO FILAMENTOS DE PEQUEÑO DIAMETRO , QUE AUMENTA LA PROBABILIDAD DE QUE LAS PARTICULAS SERAN INTERCEPTADAS POR UNA FIBRA. ESTE AUMENTO EN LA RETIRADA DE PARTICULAS, VA ACOMPAÑADO POR UN AUMENTO EN LA CAIDA DE LA PRESION. LAS CAIDAS DE PRESION EXCESIVAS PUEDEN RESTRINGIR EL FLUJO DEL AIRE Y ACORTAR LA VIDA DEL FILTRO. ESTA INVENCION PROPORCIONA EL MATERIAL DE FILTRACION QUE COMPRENDE UN TEJIDO PROVISTO DE FIBRAS CONTINUAS Y DE FIBRAS CARGADAS ELECTRICAMENTE DISPERSADAS ALEATORIAMENTE ENTRE LAS CONTINUAS. EL MATERIAL DE FILTRACION PUEDE FORMARSE EN CONFIGURACIONES PLANAS Y EN OTRAS QUE NO LO SON. column12: Sweep generator error characterization.
column13: A delay time between the start of a trace on an oscilloscope screen and a point along the trace is computed based on measured "sweep gain" and "sweep start" parameters characterizing a triggered sweep signal controlling the horizontal position of an electron beam creating the trace, the sweep signal increasing when triggered from a starting level at a constant slew rate to move the beam at a constant speed across the screen. The sweep start parameter is the value of input data applied to a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) which would cause the DAC to produce an output voltage equal to the sweep signal starting level, and the sweep gain indicates the rate of increase in DAC input data required to produce a DAC output signal with a rate of increase similar to the slew rate of the sweep signal. The horizontal position of the point along the trace is the beam position on the screen at the moment the sweep signal magnitude reaches the magnitude of the DAC output signal. The delay time is computed as the difference between the DAC input data resulting in this DAC output signal magnitude and the sweep start parameter, the difference being divided by the sweep gain parameter.

column12: FILTRATION MEDIA AND METHOD OF MANUFACTURE
column13: The present invention relates to filtration material, more particularly, filtration material that is suitable for air filtration in heating, ventilating, and air conditioning systems. The primary objective of a high performance air filter is to provide maximum particle removal while maintaining an acceptable pressure drop. Conventional fibrous filters obtain improved particle removal efficiency by using filaments having small diameter, which can be packed closely together. This close packing results in smaller voids between the fibers, which increases the probability that particles will be intercepted by a fiber. This increase in particle removal is, however, accompanied by an increase in pressure drop. Excessive pressure drops can restrict air flow and shorten filter life. This invention provides filtration material comprising a web comprising continuous, meltblown fibers and staple, electrically charged fibers randomly dispersed among the continuous fibers. The filtration material can be formed in planar configurations and in configurations other than planar. Non-planar configurations can extend the useful working area for a given filter element's cross-section without requiring an additional corrugating or pleating process step. The filtration material exhibits high strength and low pressuredrop.

column12: ADJUSTABLE BEARING SECTION CORE BARREL
column13: AN ADJUSTABLE BEARING SECTION CORE BARREL The longitudinal position of an inner barrel within a core barrel assembly can be adjusted and locked in the field without necessitating the disassembly of the cartridge cap assembly within the core barrel tool, and therefore without entailing loss of expensive rig time. The inner tube is coupled through a swivel assembly to a cartridge cap. The cartridge cap is threadedly coupled to the coring tool, and in particular to the outer tube. Thus, the cartridge cap is arranged and configured to be rotated, and thus longitudinally adjusted with respect to the outer tube. An upper portion of the cartridge cap is provided with a plurality of radially expanding fingers. A jam nut is disposed within a cylindrical array formed by the fingers, and is threadably engaged with the inside surface of the fingers. The jam nut has a frustoconical shape, and thus as the jam nut is advanced longitudinally with respect to the fingers, the fingers are urged outwardly, ultimately in a tight and locking contact with an interior surface of the coring tool. A hollow cylindrical wrench is disposed through the end of the core barrel to engage the cartridge cap and rotate it to the desired longitudinal position. A jam nut wrench is disposed through the hollow cartridge cap wrench, and when the inner tube has been appropriately adjusted is used to advance the jam nut downwardly in the fingers to expand the fingers and thus lock the longitudinal position of the cartridge cap.

column12: Assembly and system including a tibial cut guide
column13: Systems and apparatuses including a system that can be used in a knee replacement procedure are disclosed. According to one example, the system can include a tibial cut guide and an alignment guide. The tibial cut guide can have a first guide portion coupled to and adjustable relative to a second guide portion. The first guide portion can be configured to define a sagittal cut slot and the second guide portion can be configured to define a proximal cut slot. The alignment guide can be configured for extramedullary mounting to the patient and can be configured to couple with the second guide portion of the tibial cut guide. The alignment guide can have a first mechanism and a second mechanism of differing construction. The first mechanism and the second mechanism can both be configured to be actuated to facilitate extension and retraction of the alignment guide to position the tibial cut guide in a desired proximal-distal location relative a tibia of a patient when the tibial cut guide and the alignment guide are assembled together.

column12: Method for weather-based advertising
column13: A system and method that allows for weather-based planning of future activities and/or events, and the like. The system includes weather forecast, weather history, activities, advertisement and external information source databases. Also included in the system is a central processing planning server that is accessible via a plurality of internal and external workstations. The workstations provide a graphical user interface for users to enter a series of inputs and receive information (i.e., output) concerning weather-based information. The method involves collecting the series of inputs—geographic location(s), time period(s), and preferred weather pattern(s)—affecting a future event.

column12: Pressure-operated valve, particularly for a downhole pump
column13: A pressure-operated valve is provided, particularly for use with a downhole pump of the fluid-driven, successive-stage, bladder type. Such a pump includes a plurality of pump and transfer modules. The pump modules have bladders which are operated by fluid, preferably gas, under pressure supplied through two separate internal passages in the modules to pump liquid upwardly through transfer modules. The pressure-operated valve is located below the bottom of the pump module and normally closes off the two gas passages. When gas under pressure above operating pressure is supplied through one of the passages, to establish a sufficient pressure differential between the passages, the valve opens to connect the passages. Heated gas can then be circulated to increase the temperature of internal oil passages extending through the modules to prevent paraffin formation. The two gas circuits can also be connected to enable removal of condensate. Periodic opening or closing of the valve to enable one of these operations for a predetermined length of time can be done automatically or manually utilizing the surface controls provided with the pumping system.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR WEATHER-BASED ACTIVITIES PLANNING AND ADVERTISING
column13: L'invention concerne un système et un procédé permettant de planifier en fonction du temps des activités et/ou des évènements à venir. Le système comprend des prévisions météorologiques, des antécédents climatiques, des activités, des annonces publicitaires et des bases de données de sources d'informations externes. Le système comprend également un serveur de planification central, accessible via plusieurs stations de travail internes et externes. Les stations de travail fournissent une interface utilisateur graphique permettant aux utilisateurs d'introduire une série d'entrées et de recevoir des données (c'est-à-dire, des sorties) sur des informations climatiques. Le procédé consiste à collecter les séries d'entrées - emplacement(s) géographique(s), tranche(s) horaire(s) et caractéristique(s) climatique(s) préférée(s) - affectant un évènement à venir.

column12: ADJUSTABLE FLOOR TO WALL CONNECTORS FOR USE WITH BOTTOM CHORD AND WEB BEARING JOISTS
column13: The present invention is a light steel framed metal joist including an adjustable connector fastened to the joist web that allows one to adjust the length and angle of the joist when attaching to floor and wall systems. The adjustment allows one to install end connectors onto the joists prior to installation while retaining flexibility of orientation during construction. The joist functions in both web bearing and bottom chord bearing configurations. A flat plate distributing member allows one to design a floor system without having to coordinate the positioning of the joist with wall studs. Angle or U shaped members can be fastened to the lower portion of the flat plate distribution member to support joists during construction. The invention further provides a seamless fire stopping system with consideration for acoustic dampening.

column13: 본 발명은 여과 재료, 더욱 특히 난방, 환기 및 공기 조절 시스템에서 고기 여과에 적합한 여과 재료에 관한 것이다. 고성능 공기 필터의 주요 목적은 허용할 수 있는 압력차를 유지하면서 최대로 입자를 제거하는 것이다. 통상의 섬유 필터는 함께 조밀하게 팩킹시킬 수 있는 작은 직경의 필라멘트를 사용함으로써 개선된 입자 제거 효율을 수득한다. 이 조밀한 팩킹은 섬유들간에 보다 작은 공극을 생성시켜 입자들이 섬유에 의해 차단될 확률을 증대시킨다. 그러나, 이러한 입제 제거율의 증가는 압력강하의 증가를 수반한다. 과도한 압력강하는 공기의 흐름을 제한하고 필터의 수명을 단축시킨다. 본 발명은 용융블로잉된 연속 섬유 및 상기 연속 섬유사이에 랜덤하게 분산된 하전된 스테이플 섬유를 포함하는 웹을 포함한 여과 재료를 제공한다. 상기 여과 재료는 평면 구조 및 평면 이외의 구조로 제조할 수 있다. 비-평면 구조는 추가의 주름가공(corrugating or pleating process) 단계를 필요로 하지 않고도 주어진 필터 부재 단면의 유용한 작업 면적을 증대시킬 수 있다. 상기 여과 재료는 높은 강도 및 낮은 압력강하를 나타낸다.

column12: FILTRATION MEDIA AND METHOD OF MANUFACTURE
column13: 44404 CAN 7A The present invention relates to filtration material, more particularly, filtration material that is suitable for air filtration in heating, ventilating, and air conditioning systems. The primary objective of a high performance air filter is to provide maximum particle removal while maintaining an acceptable pressure drop. Conventional fibrous filters obtain improved particle removal efficiency by using filaments having small diameter, which can be packed closely together. This close packing results in smaller voids between the fibers, which increases the probability that particles will be intercepted by a fiber. This increase in particle removal is, however, accompanied by an increase in pressure drop. Excessive pressure drops can restrict air flow and shorten filter life. This invention provides filtration material comprising a web comprising continuous, meltblown fibers and staple, electrically charged fibers randomly dispersed among the continuous fibers. The filtration material can be formed in planar configurations and in configurations other than planar. Non-planar configurations can extend the useful working area for a given filter element's cross-section without requiring an additional corrugating or pleating process step. The filtration material exhibits high strength and low pressure drop.

column12: REEL FOR A HARVESTING MACHINE
column13: "REEL FOR A HARVESTING MACHINE" A reel for a harvesting machine comprises a plurality of bats arranged for rotation around an axis defined by a shaft. The bats are pivotal about a bat axis parallel to the shaft and are driven in pivoting movement by an eccentric ring member interconnected to each of the bats by a rigid link controlled by the eccentric ring member. The ring member is free to rotate relative to the shaft but is driven by each in turn of the links when the respective bat reaches an extreme position as defined by a sliding link coupled between the rigid link and the ring member. The bats comprise folded sheet metal in tubular form defining a plurality of pockets each for receiving a plastics finger for projecting from a leading edge of the bat. Each bat is formed from separate bat portions coupled together by tubes extending into an end of the bat and bolted to the tubes so as to depress material from the bat into a punched hole formed in a groove in the tube.

column12: Adjustable floor to wall connectors for use with bottom chord and web bearing joists
column13: The present invention is a light steel framed metal joist including an adjustable connector fastened to the joist web that allows one to adjust the length and angle of the joist when attaching to floor and wall systems. The adjustment allows one to install end connectors onto the joists prior to installation while retaining flexibility of orientation during construction. The joist functions in both web bearing and bottom chord bearing configurations. A flat plate distributing member allows one to design a floor system without having to coordinate the positioning of the joist with wall studs. Angle or U shaped members can be fastened to the lower portion of the flat plate distribution member to support joists during construction. The invention further provides a seamless fire stopping system with consideration for acoustic dampening.

column13: Concepts and technologies disclosed herein are directed to a cloud delivery platform. The cloud delivery platform can publish a cloud deployable offering. The cloud delivery platform can order, from a cloud orchestrator, one or more resources to be utilized by the cloud deployable offering. The cloud delivery platform can provision the cloud deployable offering on the resource(s). The cloud delivery platform can manage the cloud deployable offering to ensure that the cloud deployable offering meets a level of service. The cloud delivery platform can monitor one or more components of the cloud delivery platform to determine whether an event has occurred, and in response to determining that an event has occurred, the cloud delivery platform can broadcast the event.

column12: Improvements relating to machines for filling vessels such as bottles with liquid
column13: 732,240. Bottling. VICKERS-ARMSTRONGS, Ltd. May 19, 1953 [June 16, 1952], No. 15128/52. Class 125 (2). In counterpressure rotating-table filling machines wherein each filling head includes a liquid valve 23 at the bottom of the filling tube 13 and a counterpressure valve 37 within the filling head casing 12, these valves being moved vertically in appropriate sequence through push rods 27, 38 by a tappet plate 31 rotated about a vertical axis by a star wheel 51 engaged by stationary stops around the machine, vertical movement of the plate 31 being effected by screw threads 48, each valve has a safety ball valve in series with it to close automatically upon a surge of liquid or counterpressure. Alternatively, the plate 31 may have its operative surface 30 formed as a face cam. The machine may be of the annular tank type. As shown, however, a pipe 7 leads liquid from a central reservoir to each head into which the liquid enters through a chamber 32, port 35 and chamber 11 communicating with the filling tube 13. A rush of liquid due to e.g. a burst bottle causes a phosphor bronze ball 33 to close the port 35. Closing of liquid valve 23 at the end of a cycle causes a collar 36 on stem 27 to knock the ball 33 out of seating 35. Counterpressure from a central water-column levelling vessel is transmitted through pipes 10 to a chamber 43 in each head. Thence, it passes through a port 42, a valve chamber 14 and conduits 15, 16 and 22 to the bottle. Valve 37 is at the lower end of chamber 42 and a ball 44 closes the port 42 in the event of a rush of gas. A shoulder 46 is so disposed on the rod 38 that the ball is knocked out of the port when the valve 37 is in its half open position or as it is moved from fully open to closed position. The valves are closed by springs 25, 41. In operation, the bottle is raised to engage member 20 which rises to cause gasket 18<SP>1</SP> to seat against gasket 17<SP>1</SP>. Star-wheel 51 is actuated to move valve 37 to half-open position to supply counterpressure. On further actuation of star-wheel 51, valve 37 is fully opened and the liquid valve 23 is also opened. The star-wheel is then, after filling, restored to its original position to allow the valves to close and the filled bottle is lowered. Specifications 503,927, 600,359 and 722,358 are referred to.

column12: FLUID HEAT TRANSFER SYSTEM FOR ANIMAL DIAGNOSTIC BED AND METHODS OF USING THE SAME
column13: A diagnostic system is disclosed, and comprises a diagnostic device and a fluid heat transfer system. The diagnostic device has an associated bed for supporting a portion of a subject during a diagnostic procedure. The fluid heat transfer system comprises a fluid circulation component, a heater component, and a fluid line. column12: A machine for the administration of anaesthetic gases or for the ventilation of an apnoeic patient
column13: 1,008,520. Respiratory appliances. CAPE ENGINEERING CO Ltd and BYFIELD INVESTMENTS Ltd. Oct. 12, 1962 [Oct. 14, 1961], No. 36947/61. Heading A5T. A respiratory apparatus, which may be used for administering of anaesthetic or for forced breathing, has means for changing from automatic to manual operation or vice versa at will. The changeover is primarily effected by a selector valve assembly comprising three gauged valves 14, 13, 66 and, in the position shown oxygen or. other gas, received through flowmeters 2 or from an emergency supply 65, is fed into a duct 6 and any excess is accommodated in a bag 3. A positive pressure bellows, actuated by a shaft 81, forces it in the direction of the arrows 8 part a mechanically controlled valve 12 and connection 15 to the patient and subsequently, also actuated by the shaft 31, a valve 18 is opened and a second bellows 21 withdraws the gas from the patients lungs, through a carbon dioxide absorber 23 for recirculation, any excess in this case being accommodated in a bag 25. The timing of the breathing cycle is adjusted by a variable ratio gear-box 32 connected to the driving motor 30 and the volume passed at each cycle is adjusted by changing the position of the fulcrum of the lever 40 which extends between the bellows 9 and its actuating crank 37. When the selector valve assembly 66, 13, 14 is rotated anti-clockwise through 90 degrees a switch, not shown, stops the motor 30 and gas from inlet pipe 1 passes directly, through pipe 68, to the part of the circuit to the right of the valves 13, 14, which is now isolated from the rest of the equipment. In addition, a rebreathing bag 60 is connected through non-return valves to this effective part of the circuit so that by manually squeezing and releasing the bag 60 an operator can force gas into the patient's lungs, in the direction of the arrow 8, and withdraw it, through the carbon dioxide absorber 23, as indicated by the arrow 17. Spring loaded relief valves 28, 74, 75 are provided to prevent the building up of excessive pressures and a valve 20 limits the degree of suction which can be applied to the patient.

column12: Improvements in filling heads for bottle-filling machines
column13: 792,262. Bottling. FOX & CO., Ltd., D. Aug. 18, 1955 [Sept. 24, 1954], No. 27730/54. Class 125(2). In rotating table counterpressure bottling machines having filling tubes 26 the lower ends of which are closed by pear valves 27 closed by springs 30 and opened by fluid pressure acting on a piston 29, a single rotatable plug cock 14 actuated step by step by stationary trips supplies counterpressure and fluid pressure for actuating pistons 29 to each pair of filling tubes 26, a check valve 21 being provided for cutting off the counterpressure if a bottle should burst, but being prevented from closing during the application of counterpressure. As shown, extensions 102, 103 of a central body 10 are each provided with a depending filling tube 26 and the body 10 contains a vertical bore 11 containing a vertical plug cock 14 the shaft of which is extended upwardly and the end thereof is connected with a certain amount of lost motion to a star wheel 151 so that shock occurring when the trips actuate the star wheel is largely absorbed. Counterpressure is supplied through passages 19, 17 to the space 11 and bottling liquid through passages 20, 18 and a pair of passages 36 to chambers 24 communicating with the filling tubes 26. In operation, the parts are initially in a first stage in which the pear valves 27 are closed by springs 30 and the ports of cock 14 are also closed ; during this stage each bottle is raised to contact and raise a guide bell 32, a gasket 322 on which seats an annulus 253 fixed to the bottom of extensions 102, 103. The cock 14 is then rotated by the first trip to the second stage in which counterpressure can flow through passages 37 in the cock and passages 33, 34, 341 to the bottle ; during this stage the check valve 21 in the counterpressure supply is held from its seat by a projection 143 on the cock. The second trip then rotates the cock to the third stage in which the passages 37 still connect space 111 to passages 33 and also connect the space through passages 31 to space 221 above the piston 29 so that the counterpressure forces down the piston and opens valve 27 to allow liquid to flow into the bottle. During this stage, check valve 21 can move to its seat should a bottle burst and the passages are vented to atmosphere through the burst bottle so allowing spring 30 to close valve 27 ; also during this stage displaced gas flows from the bottle in reverse direction through passages 341, 34 and 33. The third trip then moves cock 14 to the fourth stage in which passages 38, 39, 40 therein connect passages 31, 33 to atmosphere so that spring 30 closes liquid valve 27 and the bottle head space is snifted. The cock is then turned to its initial position and the filled bottles are lowered. According to the Provisional Specification, the plug cock controls a single filling tube assembly only.

column12: Systems And Methods For Performing Fiber Node Splits Using Remote QAM Modulation And Demodulation
column13: Systems and methods are provided for performing fiber node splits in DOCSIS cable systems by performing remote modulation and/or demodulation in the fiber node. In the downstream direction, a high-speed digital fiber optic interface can be used to send data from the CMTS to the fiber node, which then modulates the data onto separate downstream interfaces for subsequent distribution of the downstream data to CMs and/or STBs. In the upstream direction, different upstream interfaces from the CMs and/or STBs may be demodulated into digital streams which can then be combined into a single, time division multiplexed digital stream that is transmitted to the CMTS. As such, the modulation and demodulation functions are performed remotely in the fiber node instead of at the CMTS. This allows the fiber portion of the network to use less-expensive, off-the-shelf networking technologies such as Ethernet, and allows for more data to be sent over the fiber network such that additional fibers and/or wavelengths are not required when performing a node split.

column12: Position-sensitive shock absorber
column13: The present invention is directed to shock absorbers, including position-sensitive shock absorbers (2) in which the position-sensitive damping can be different during compression and rebound strokes, and shock absorbers (60) with damping adjusters (80, 118) which vary the damping provided during compression and rebound strokes. The position-sensitive shock absorber includes a cylinder (4) within which a piston (122) is movably mounted for movement between the first and second ends of the cylinder. Bypass openings (24-32) open into the cylinder interior (6) at axially spaced-apart positions. The bypass openings are coupled by a bypass channel (38). A flow valve (40, 42) may be positioned along the bypass channel permitting fluid flow from the first opening to the second opening and restricting fluid flow from the second opening to the first opening. A pressurized gas container (18) may be fluidly coupled to the cylinder interior with a movable barrier (14) separating the pressurized gas container and the cylinder interior.

column12: Accelerator system stabilization for charged particle acceleration and radiation beam generation
column13: A method for generating stabilized particle acceleration by a radio-frequency (RF) accelerator is described, comprising operating the accelerator in a warm-up mode during a warm-up time period, without injecting charged particles or without accelerating injected charged particles, and operating the accelerator in a beam-on mode during a beam-on time period after the warm-up time period, to accelerate charged particles injected by the charged particle source. Automatic frequency control to match an expected frequency of the accelerator during the beam-on time period, prior to the start of the beam-on time period, for stability, is also described.

column12: Fluid jet cutting method and apparatus
column13: A fluid jet cutting method and apparatus for cutting an object from a sheet. In one embodiment, a fluid jet stream is directed against a glass sheet to cut an annular disk substrate for use in a data storage device. The sheet is supported by first, second and third support members. The support surfaces of the second and third support members are respectively positioned inside central openings in the first and second support members. A vacuum pulls the sheet against the support surface of at least the second support member. Preferably, plural central openings in the first support member accommodate plural second and third support members, whereby plural substrates are cut from the sheet. The sheet preferably includes plural layers removably adhered to one another, whereby plural substrates are simultaneously formed by a single fluid jet stream. A protective layer may cover at least one surface to the sheet.

column12: Multi-function binding system
column13: A multi-function binding system configured for use on a sliding board comprising: (a) a binding operable with a boot assembly, the binding comprising a support surface and toe and heel pieces extending therefrom; (b) a base assembly configured to be rotatably and removably secured to a deck of a sliding board and to releasably couple the binding during use of the sliding board, the base assembly comprising: (i) a support disc configured to be removably coupled to the deck of the sliding board and to secure the base assembly to the sliding board; (ii) a deck plate rotatable about the support disc and configured to be positioned adjacent the deck; (iii) a bonnet also rotatable about the support disc and configured to receive and engage the binding, the bonnet operable with the deck plate to support one or more components of the base assembly; (iv) adjustment means for facilitating the rotational adjustment of the bonnet and the deck plate about the support disc and with respect to the sliding board, thereby facilitating a plurality of stance orientations of the boot assembly with respect to the sliding board, the adjustment means configured to selectively engage the support disc at any one of a plurality of adjustment positions; (v) coupling means configured to releasably couple the binding to the base assembly, and therefore the boot system to the sliding board, thereby securing a user thereto; and (vi) release means for actuating the coupling means to release the binding from the base assembly, and therefore the boot system from the sliding board.

column12: ROLL FORMED STEEL BEAM
column13: The present invention relates to a cold rolled steel beam comprising: a web having two layers of steel, the web having a top end and a bottom end; a pair of bottom flanges extending outwardly from the bottom end of the web; and a pair of top flanges extending outwardly from the top end of the web, each top flange having two layers of steel. Preferably, the cold rolled steel beam is cold formed from a unitary piece of sheet steel.

column12: Position-sensitive shock absorber
column13: The present invention is directed to shock absorbers with damping adjusters which vary the damping provided during compression and rebound strokes. The shock absorber includes a cylinder within which a piston is movably mounted for movement within the cylinder. Bypass openings open into the cylinder interior at axially spaced-apart positions. The bypass openings are coupled by a bypass channel. A pressurized gas container is fluidly coupled to the cylinder interior with a movable barrier separating the pressurized gas container and the cylinder interior. Compression and rebound damping adjusters may be used.

column12: Light steel trusses and truss systems
column13: A truss chord for use in a light steel truss includes a flange portion, a pair of web portions and at least one wing. The flange portion has an end and an end portion. The end portion has a double thickness. The pair of web portions extend substantially orthogonally from the flange portion and are spaced inwardly from the ends of the flange portion. The at least one wing extends outwardly substantially orthogonally from at least one of the pair of web portions. There is provided an alternate embodiment wherein the wing having a plurality of spaced apart holes formed therein. There is also provided a truss web. As well there is a truss which uses the truss chords and truss webs and a truss system which uses a plurality of trusses. In addition there is a mass customization system for the trusses.

column12: COMPOSITE STEEL JOIST
column13: The present disclosure relates to a steel joist assembly for use in association with a concrete slab and being adapted to form a composite steel joist including a steel joist and a pair of end connectors. The steel joist has a top portion with a generally planar top surface and a planar web generally orthogonal to the generally planar top surface. An end connector is attached at each end of the steel joist. Each end connector has a strut and a diagonal member. The strut has a generally planar bottom surface which is attached to a portion of the generally planar top surface of the steel joist and the diagonal member is attached at one end thereof to the strut and at the other end thereof to a portion of the planar web of the steel joist.

column12: Multi-function binding system
column13: A multi-function binding system configured for use on a sliding board, such as a snowboard or wakeboard, comprising a base assembly rotatably secured to the deck of a sliding board, with a binding system operable with the base assembly to releasably secure a user to the sliding board. column12: MULTI-FUNCTION BINDING SYSTEM
column13: A multi-function binding system configured for interchangeable use on a plurality of different sliding board, such as a snowboard or wakeboard, comprising a base assembly rotatably secured to the deck of a sliding board, with a binding system operable with the base assembly to releasably secure a user to the sliding board. The base assembly comprises various components, namely an adjustment mechanism and a release mechanism, supported within a bonnet that is rotatable about a support disc designed to be secured to the sliding board via the mounting configuration of the sliding board. The binding system provides a unique and advantageous release function otherwise not available in prior related binding systems.

column12: ASSEMBLY AND SYSTEM INCLUDING A TIBIAL CUT GUIDE
column13: A system that can be used in a knee replacement procedure can include a tibial cut guide and an alignment guide. The tibial cut guide can have a first guide portion coupled to and adjustable relative to a second guide portion. The first guide portion can be configured to define a sagittal cut slot and a proximal cut slot. The alignment guide configured for extramedullary mounting to the patient and configured to couple with the second guide portion of the tibial cut guide, the alignment guide having a first mechanism and a second mechanism of differing construction, the first mechanism and the second mechanism are both configured to be actuated to facilitate extension and retraction of the alignment guide to position the tibial cut guide in a desired proximal-distal location relative a tibia of a patient when the tibial cut guide and the alignment guide are assembled together.

column12: Methods of restoring operation of serial ATA storage devices
column13: The present invention relates to systems and methods for providing multiple access paths to a single ported storage device used in data storage subsystems. In an embodiment, the system provides circuitry associated with single ported storage devices, including a coupling circuit with a microcontroller for signals which include the data and control paths to and from redundant storage device controllers. In this embodiment, the additional control in the form of discrete signal lines or through additional commands is used to manage routing of the signals to and from a redundant data storage controller. Further, each redundant data storage controller preferably has its own primary set of storage devices. If one of the controllers fails, the redundant controller can switch its control to the failed controller's storage devices thus maintaining user access to the data contained on those storage devices.

column12: Composite steel joist
column13: The present disclosure relates to a steel joist assembly for use in association with a concrete slab and being adapted to form a composite steel joist including a steel joist and a pair of end connectors. The steel joist has a top portion with a generally planar top surface and a planar web generally orthogonal to the generally planar top surface. An end connector is attached at each end of the steel joist. Each end connector has a strut and a diagonal member. The strut has a generally planar bottom surface which is attached to a portion of the generally planar top surface of the steel joist and the diagonal member is attached at one end thereof to the strut and at the other end thereof to a portion of the planar web of the steel joist.

column12: Light Steel Trusses and Truss Systems
column13: A truss chord for use in a light steel truss includes a flange portion, a pair of web portions and at least one wing. The flange portion has an end and an end portion. The end portion has a double thickness. The pair of web portions extend substantially orthogonally from the flange portion and are spaced inwardly from the ends of the flange portion. The at least one wing extends outwardly substantially orthogonally from at least one of the pair of web portions. There is provided an alternate embodiment wherein the wing having a plurality of spaced apart holes formed therein. There is also provided a truss web. As well there is a truss which uses the truss chords and truss webs and a truss system which uses a plurality of trusses. In addition there is a mass customization system for the trusses.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR THE ADVANCED PREDICTION OF WEATHER IMPACT ON MANAGERIAL PLANNING APPLICATIONS
column13: A computer-based system (102) and method which incorporates long-range weather forecasts in a predictive model (128) which quantifies historical weather impact relationships between datasets, and uses the long-range weather forecasts to predict future weather impact on managerial plans. The predictive model (130) can use multiple regression or a neural network. In a retail application, the computer-based system and method has a weather impact predictive model based on correlations of historical weather and point-of-sale store transactions data. The weather impact model is coupled with long-range weather forecasts to adjust managerial plans for buying, distribution, financial budgeting, promotional and advertising applications. A graphical user interface provides easy assimilation of analysis for specific managerial planning applications.

column12: Augennahe Anzeigen mit optischer Dekonvolution
column13: Eine Vorrichtung aufweisend:eine Anzeige (624, 824, 1124) aufweisend mehrere Pixel (722, 725), die zum Emittieren von Licht betriebsfähig sind;ein Computersystem, das mit der Anzeige gekoppelt ist und betriebsfähig ist, die Anzeige anzuweisen, ein entfaltetes Bild (1212) anzuzeigen, das zu einem Zielbild (1204) korrespondiert, wobei, wenn die Anzeige das entfaltete Bild anzeigt während sie in einem augennahen Bereich (218) eines Beobachters angeordnet ist, das Zielbild von dem Beobachter fokussiert wahrgenommen werden kann,wobei ein Prozessor des Computersystems betriebsfähig ist, das entfaltete Bild durch Ausführen einer Konvolutionsoperation an einer ersten Funktion mit einer Inversen einer zweiten Funktion zu bestimmen, wobei die erste Funktion das Zielbild beschreibt, wobei die zweite Funktion einen Verschwimmungseffekt eines defokussierten Auges beschreibt, das versucht, eine Ebene außerhalb eines Akkomodationsabstands des Auges und innerhalb des augennahen Bereichs zu betrachten, und wobei der Prozessor betriebsfähig ist, das entfaltete Bild zu filtern, damit es innerhalb eines dynamischen Bereichs der Anzeige ist, so dass die Anzeige zum Anzeigen des gefilterten entfalteten Bildes betriebsfähig ist,wobei das entfaltete Bild außerhalb des Fokus ist, wenn es außerhalb des augennahen Bereichs betrachtet wird, und wobei das entfaltete Bild fokussiert ist, wenn es innerhalb des augennahen Bereichs betrachtet wird.
column15: LUEBKE DAVID PATRICK;;LANMAN DOUGLAS;;FOX THOMAS F;;SLAVENBURG GERRIT

column12: NEAR-EYE PARALLAX BARRIER DISPLAYS
column13: In embodiments of the invention, an apparatus may include a display comprising a plurality of pixels and a computer system coupled with the display and operable to instruct the display to display images. The apparatus may further include an SLM array located adjacent to the display and comprising a plurality of SLMs, wherein the SLM array is operable to produce a light field by altering light emitted by the display to simulate an object that is in focus to an observer while the display and the SLM array are located within a near-eye range of the observer.

column12: BEHIND PIPE EVALUATION TECHNIQUES FOR WELL ABANDONMENT AND COMPLEX ANNULAR ENVIRONMENTS.
column13: A method includes introducing a tool string into a wellbore having annular material disposed in an annulus defined between casing and the wellbore. Obtaining acoustic refracted waveform measurements of the annular material from a cement bond logging tool, obtaining ultrasonic measurements of the annular material from a circumferential acoustic scanning tool, obtaining gamma radiation measurements scattered from the annular material from a spectral density logging tool, and obtaining thermal neutron radiation measurements scattered from the annular material from a dual spaced neutron logging tool. Obtained measurements may then be collected and computed with a computer and a deliverable is generated that includes one or more cross plots providing a compositional equivalent of the annular material.

column12: Near-eye Optical Deconvolution Display
column13: The present invention discloses a near-eye optical deconvolution display. In embodiments of the invention, an apparatus may include a display comprising a plurality of pixels. The apparatus may further include a computer system coupled with the display and operable to instruct the display to display a deconvolved image corresponding to a target image, wherein when the display displays the deconvolved image while located within a near-eye range of an observer, the target image may be perceived in focus by the observer.

column12: INTELLIGENT NODE FOR IMPROVING SIGNAL QUALITY IN A CABLE MODEM NETWORK
column13: Systems and methods are provided for improving the signal quality and performance in a cable operator's Hybrid Fiber Coax (HFC) plant by adding DOCSIS intelligence to components within the HFC plant. These intelligent DOCSIS devices, referred to here as DOCSIS Intelligent Nodes (DINs), intercept the upstream signal from cable modems and set top boxes, and perform various types of signal processing on the signals based upon knowledge of the signal characteristics obtained from CMTS control structures such as MAPs and Upstream Channel Descriptors (UCDs). The DIN functionality can be integrated into any type of device found in HFC networks such as RF amplifiers and fiber nodes.

column12: NEAR-EYE PARALLAX BARRIER DISPLAYS
column13: In embodiments of the invention, a method may include displaying an array of slits using a first light-attenuating spatial light modulator, displaying a pre-filtered image using a second light-attenuating SLM by attenuating rays of light originating from a surrounding environment to synthesis a near-eye light field, where the rays of light pass through the first and second light-attenuating SLMs, and selectively blocking the rays of light originating from the surrounding environment using the array of slits to generate a virtual image in said near-eye light field.

column12: Augennahe Anzeige mit Mikrolinsen-Array
column13: Eine Vorrichtung aufweisend:eine Anzeige (124, 324, 624) aufweisend mehrere Pixel (512, 522, 524, 532);ein Computersystem, das mit der Anzeige gekoppelt und betriebsfähig ist, die Anzeige zum Anzeigen von Bildern anzuweisen; undein Mikrolinsen-Array (328, 328b), das benachbart zu der Anzeige angeordnet ist und mehrere Mikrolinsen (516, 526, 536) aufweist, wobei das Mikrolinsen-Array betriebsfähig ist, ein Lichtfeld zu erzeugen, indem Licht, das von der Anzeige ausgesendet wird, verändert wird, um ein Objekt zu simulieren, das für einen Beobachter fokussiert ist, während die Anzeige und das Mikrolinsen-Array innerhalb eines augennahen Bereich des Beobachters angeordnet sind,wobei eine erste Mehrzahl von Strahlen gleichmäßig in alle Richtungen von einem ersten Pixel (512) der Anzeige (124, 324, 624) ausgesendet wird und von dem ersten Pixel mittels einer ersten Mikrolinse (516) empfangen wird, die konfiguriert ist zum Lenken der ersten Mehrzahl von Strahlen, so dass diese parallel in eine Mehrzahl von ersten Richtungen basierend auf einer Position des ersten Pixels relativ zu der ersten Mikrolinse wandern, und wobei eine zweite Mehrzahl von Strahlen, die gleichmäßig in alle Richtungen von einem zweiten Pixel (522) ausgesendet wird, von dem zweiten Pixel mittels einer zweiten Mikrolinse (526) empfangen wird, die konfiguriert ist zum Lenken der zweiten Mehrzahl von Strahlen, so dass diese parallel in eine Mehrzahl von zweiten Richtungen basierend auf einer Position des zweiten Pixels relativ zu der zweiten Mikrolinse wandern.

column12: Intelligent node for improving signal quality in a cable modem network
column13: Systems and methods are provided for improving the signal quality and performance in a cable operator's Hybrid Fiber Coax (HFC) plant by adding DOCSIS intelligence to components within the HFC plant. These intelligent DOCSIS devices, referred to here as DOCSIS Intelligent Nodes (DINs), intercept the upstream signal from cable modems and set top boxes, and perform various types of signal processing on the signals based upon knowledge of the signal characteristics obtained from CMTS control structures such as MAPs and Upstream Channel Descriptors (UCDs). The DIN functionality can be integrated into any type of device found in HFC networks such as RF amplifiers and fiber nodes.

column12: Behind pipe evaluation techniques for well abandonment and complex annular environments
column13: A method includes introducing a tool string into a wellbore having annular material disposed in an annulus defined between casing and the wellbore. Obtaining acoustic refracted waveform measurements of the annular material from a cement bond logging tool, obtaining ultrasonic measurements of the annular material from a circumferential acoustic scanning tool, obtaining gamma radiation measurements scattered from the annular material from a spectral density logging tool, and obtaining thermal neutron radiation measurements scattered from the annular material from a dual spaced neutron logging tool. Obtained measurements may then be collected and computed with a computer and a deliverable is generated that includes one or more cross plots providing a compositional equivalent of the annular material.

column12: REDUCED CODON MUTAGENESIS
column13: Methods and compositions that reduce complexity of libraries of variant biological molecules, that reduce oversampling of these libraries during screening and that improve screening efficiency are provided. Sets of efficient degenerate codon sets are provided that efficiently encode all, or nearly all canonical amino acids. Degenerate oligonucleotides comprising these codons are provided, as are polynucleotide variants. Variant pooling strategies are used during library construction. Logical filtering is applied to select codon sites for mutagenesis, or to select amino acid sets to be incorporated at such sites. Methods for reducing non-optimal oversampling during screening are provided.

column12: Performing software testing with best possible user experience
column13: A computer-implemented method, system and computer program product for testing a software application. User interactions with the functional and non-functional aspects of software applications are monitored. User experience profiles are then generated for the monitored users based on the monitored interactions. The best user experiences in connection with interacting with specific functional and non-functional aspects of the software applications are then identified based on the generated user experience profiles. Virtual users having different types of best user experiences in connection with interacting with different functional and non-functional aspects of the software applications are created. The software application is then tested using the virtual users to determine if the functional and non-functional aspects of the software application satisfy the best user experiences associated with the virtual users. A message may be generated indicating which functional and/or non-functional aspects of the software application did not satisfy a virtual user's best user experience.

column12: Method and apparatus for controlling airflow with a leading edge device having a flexible flow surface
column13: Methods and apparatuses for controlling airflow with a leading edge device having a flexible flow surface. In one embodiment, the airfoil includes a first portion having a first flow surface and a second flow surface facing opposite from the first flow surface. The second portion of the airfoil has a leading edge and is movably coupled to the first position. The second portion can move between a first position and a second position offset from the first position by an angle of from about 45 to about 90 or more. The second portion includes a flexible flow surface having a first shape when the second portion is in the first position and a second shape different than the first shape when the second portion is in the second position. A guide structure can be coupled between the first portion and the second portion. In another embodiment, the airfoil can have inbound and outbound leading edge portions with an inbound guide structure having a first mechanical arrangement and an outbound guide structure having a second mechanical arrangement different than the first.

column12: Performing software testing with best possible user experience
column13: A computer-implemented method, system and computer program product for testing a software application. User interactions with the functional and non-functional aspects of software applications are monitored. User experience profiles are then generated for the monitored users based on the monitored interactions. The best user experiences in connection with interacting with specific functional and non-functional aspects of the software applications are then identified based on the generated user experience profiles. Virtual users having different types of best user experiences in connection with interacting with different functional and non-functional aspects of the software applications are created. The software application is then tested using the virtual users to determine if the functional and non-functional aspects of the software application satisfy the best user experiences associated with the virtual users. A message may be generated indicating which functional and/or non-functional aspects of the software application did not satisfy a virtual user's best user experience.
column15: MILLER GRANT DOUGLAS;;CHUNG ALAN;;FOX JEREMY R;;RAKSHIT SARBAJIT K

column12: Method and apparatus for controlling airflow with a leading edge device having a flexible flow surface
column13: Methods and apparatuses for controlling airflow with a leading edge device having a flexible flow surface. In one embodiment, the airfoil includes a first portion having a first flow surface and a second flow surface facing opposite from the first flow surface. The second portion of the airfoil has a leading edge and is movably coupled to the first position. The second portion can move between a first position and a second position offset from the first position by an angle of from about 45 to about 90 or more. The second portion includes a flexible flow surface having a first shape when the second portion is in the first position and a second shape different than the first shape when the second portion is in the second position. A guide structure can be coupled between the first portion and the second portion. In another embodiment, the airfoil can have inbound and outbound leading edge portions with an inbound guide structure having a first mechanical arrangement and an outbound guide structure having a second mechanical arrangement different than the first.

column12: CATALYTIC PREPARATION OF ORGANIC HYPOCHLORITES
column13: 1,273,408. Fluorine-containing hypochlorites. ALLIED CHEMICAL CORP. 12 Nov., 1969 [21 Nov., 1968], No. 55462/69. Heading C2C. Hypochlorites of formula A(OC1) n wherein n is 1 or 2 and A is an alkyl or alkylene radical in which all the hydrogen atoms have been replaced by halogen atoms or optionally one or two electronegative groups neutral to the hypochlorite group, the carbon atom or atoms bearing the hypochlorite group or groups being attached thereto at least one fluorine atom and, when n is 2, the carbon atoms bearing hypochlorite groups not being directly attached, are prepared by reaction of an inorganic chlorinating agent containing a chlorine atom in a (+1) oxidation state and attached to an oxygen or fluorine atom with a compound containing one or more carbonyl groups not forming part of an aldehyde group in the presence as catalyst of HF, BF 3 , AsF 3 , SbF s , NOF, an NOF treated metal surface or an NOF-treated fluoroolefin polymer surface. Electronegative substituents specified are -SO 2 F, -SO 3 F, -NO 2 , perfluorocycloalkyl and perfluoroaryl groups. Chlorinating agents specified are ClF, Cl 2 O, ClONO 2 , NaOCl and ClOSO 2 F. The NOF-treated metal or fluoroolefin polymer surface may be the wall of the reaction vessel. The products are chlorinating agents, insecticidal fumigants and polymerization initiators.

column12: Abrasive fluid jet cutting composition, method and apparatus
column13: An abrasive fluid jet cutting composition, method and apparatus for cutting an object from a sheet. In one embodiment, a fluid jet stream is directed against a glass sheet to cut a disk substrate for use in a data storage device. An abrasive slurry is delivered to a fluid jet head from a slurry tank. The slurry is formed by mixing water, abrasive particles, a surfactant or surfactants, and an acid or base. The head also receives a pressurized fluid from a fluid pump. The abrasive slurry and the pressurized fluid are mixed in the head to form the fluid jet stream. Preferably, the abrasive particles are 8-64 microns and may include recycled scrap. The slurry may also contain polishing particles that are smaller than the abrasive particles to affect polishing. In addition to reducing surface tension, the surfactant may cause the abrasive particles to flocculate or disperse.

column12: Methods and data storage subsystems of controlling serial ATA storage devices
column13: The present invention relates to systems and methods for providing multiple access paths to a single ported storage device used in data storage subsystems. In an embodiment, the system provides circuitry associated with single ported storage devices, including a coupling circuit with a microcontroller for signals which include the data and control paths to and from redundant storage device controllers. In this embodiment, the additional control in the form of discrete signal lines or through additional commands is used to manage routing of the signals to and from a redundant data storage controller. Further, each redundant data storage controller preferably has its own primary set of storage devices. If one of the controllers fails, the redundant controller can switch its control to the failed controller's storage devices thus maintaining user access to the data contained on those storage devices.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR DETERMINING THE IMPACT OF WEATHER AND OTHER FACTORS ON MANAGERIAL PLANNING APPLICATIONS
column13: A computer-based Executive Information System (202) for determining the impact of weather and other external and internal factors on the retail industry. Utilizing a multiple regression correlation technique in a predictive model, a correlation of weather variables with store information for specific locations and times is performed to quantify a weather impact model in terms of unit or dollar sales volume change, or any other commercially useful benchmark (704). The Executive Information System determines these relationships with location and time specificity. Using the relationship between historical weather and historical sales, the system 'deweatherizes' the historical weather to create a normalized historical sales relative to weather based on the 30 years average normal weather (720). The deweatherized data may be used in conjunction with a user-provided managerial plan to produce a revised managerial plan (207). Alternatively, the revised plan can be 'weatherized' by the system by applying forecasted weather to the weather impact model to generate a weather-modified managerial plan (204).
